<p>Colorado's economy has undergone a dramatic transformation from its traditional mining and ranching base into one of the most dynamic and diversified in the Mountain West. Denver has become a tech hub of significant scale, home to companies like Palantir, Gusto, Ibotta, and dozens of aerospace and defense contractors. Boulder's technology and clean energy ecosystem is one of the most innovation-dense per capita in the country. Colorado Springs hosts major military installations including NORAD and the United States Space Force, along with defense contractors like Lockheed Martin and Raytheon. Tourism centered on world-class ski resorts at Vail, Aspen, Breckenridge, and Steamboat Springs generates billions in economic activity and employs tens of thousands of seasonal workers.</p>

<p>Colorado's income tax is a flat 4.4%, reduced from the prior 4.55% rate in 2022 under Proposition 121. Colorado also has a mandatory earnings statement requirement under the COMPS Order, making it one of the states where pay stub provision is legally required. This generator calculates Colorado's 4.4% flat tax and all federal taxes to produce a complete, professional pay stub PDF.</p>

<h2>Colorado Income Tax Rates</h2>

<p>Colorado uses a flat income tax rate of 4.4% on all Colorado taxable income (as of 2022 forward). Prior to the Proposition 121 reduction, the rate was 4.55%. The flat nature of the tax means all income levels pay the same percentage, with no graduated brackets.</p>

<p>Colorado's income tax uses federal adjusted gross income (AGI) as its starting point, with a modest Colorado standard deduction ($13,850 for single filers in 2024, matching the federal standard deduction). Pre-tax retirement contributions that reduce federal AGI also reduce Colorado taxable income, making 401(k) contributions doubly beneficial in Colorado.</p>

<p>Colorado also has a unique "TABOR" (Taxpayer's Bill of Rights) provision that can result in tax refunds being issued to residents when state revenue collections exceed TABOR limits. In recent high-revenue years, Colorado residents received TABOR refunds. These are credits on your Colorado income tax return, not payroll deductions, but they mean that the effective annual income tax burden can be lower than 4.4% in high-revenue years.</p>

<p>Colorado does not have local income taxes. Denver, Colorado Springs, and Boulder do not impose city income taxes on wages, keeping Colorado's payroll structure simple.</p>

<h2>Does Colorado Require Pay Stubs?</h2>

<p>Yes. The Colorado COMPS (Colorado Overtime and Minimum Pay Standards) Order requires employers to provide an earnings statement at each payday. This makes Colorado one of the states with a mandatory pay stub requirement, though the enforcement mechanism differs from states like California and New York.</p>

<p>The COMPS Order is issued annually by the Colorado Department of Labor and Employment and covers minimum wage, overtime, and record-keeping requirements. Violations can result in civil penalties and back wages. Colorado workers who are not receiving pay stubs can file wage complaints with the CDLE.</p>

<h2>Pay Stub Requirements in Colorado</h2>

<p>Under the COMPS Order, Colorado earnings statements must include:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Gross wages earned for the pay period</li>
  <li>All deductions made, itemized separately</li>
  <li>Net wages paid</li>
  <li>Date of payment and pay period covered</li>
  <li>Employer's name and address</li>
  <li>Employee identification</li>
  <li>For hourly workers: hours worked and hourly rate</li>
</ul>

<p>Colorado's Equal Pay for Equal Work Act (EPEWA) also has pay transparency requirements -- while these primarily require employers to post pay ranges in job listings, they reinforce a culture of compensation transparency that extends to pay stub documentation standards.</p>

<h2>Pay Frequency Laws in Colorado</h2>

<p>Colorado Revised Statutes § 8-4-105 requires that wages be paid not less than once per month. However, the COMPS Order and practical business norms mean most Colorado employers pay bi-weekly or semi-monthly. Monthly pay is the technical minimum but is uncommon in practice.</p>

<p>Colorado has specific rules about when wages must be paid after separation: within 10 days of termination, or on the next regular payday (whichever comes first). Unlike California, which requires immediate payment upon involuntary termination, Colorado allows up to 10 days.</p>

<p>Colorado's overtime law follows the federal FLSA standard (after 40 hours per week), with one addition: overtime also applies after 12 hours in a single workday. This daily overtime trigger (borrowed partially from California's approach) affects industries like restaurants, ski resorts, and construction where 12-plus hour days are common.</p>

<h2>Colorado's Industries and Who Uses Pay Stubs</h2>

<p><strong>Ski and mountain resort workers:</strong> Colorado's ski industry employs tens of thousands of seasonal workers at Vail, Breckenridge, Keystone, Steamboat, and dozens of other resorts. These workers -- ski instructors, lift operators, lodge staff, snowmakers -- are often seasonal employees earning hourly wages. The mountain resort rental markets (Vail, Aspen, Steamboat Springs) are among the most expensive in the country, and landlords in these areas require income documentation. Seasonal workers whose income is concentrated in winter months need to document that income accurately for year-round housing applications. See our <a href="/hourly-pay-stub-template">hourly pay stub template</a> for structuring seasonal hourly income documentation.</p>

<p><strong>Denver tech workers:</strong> Denver's tech sector has exploded, with companies like Palantir, Gusto (relocated from San Francisco), Ibotta, and Arrow Electronics building significant presences. Many tech workers work as contractors, between funding rounds at startups, or in consulting roles. Denver's competitive rental market in neighborhoods like LoDo, RiNo, and Capitol Hill means tech workers need solid income documentation.</p>

<p><strong>Aerospace and defense contractors:</strong> Colorado has enormous aerospace presence: Lockheed Martin Space in Littleton, Raytheon Intelligence and Space in Aurora, the United States Space Force (with Space Command at Peterson AFB in Colorado Springs), NORAD, and dozens of smaller defense contractors. Many aerospace workers are on time-limited contracts and need income documentation for mortgage applications as they settle in the Front Range communities.</p>

<p><strong>Cannabis industry workers:</strong> Colorado was the first state to legalize recreational cannabis in 2012. The cannabis industry now employs tens of thousands, from budtenders and extraction technicians to dispensary managers. Cannabis businesses operate entirely in cash at the wholesale level (federal banking restrictions on cannabis businesses create unique payroll documentation challenges), but employees still receive paychecks and need standard pay documentation. Generated stubs for cannabis workers use the same format as any other industry.</p>


