<h2>Frequently Asked Questions for Colorado Workers</h2>

<h3>Colorado has daily overtime after 12 hours. How does this show on my pay stub?</h3>
<p>Colorado's daily overtime rule means that hours worked beyond 12 in a single day are paid at 1.5x, even if total weekly hours do not exceed 40. For a ski resort worker who works a 14-hour day during a peak holiday period, hours 13 and 14 are overtime even if the rest of the week was slow. The pay stub should show regular hours, weekly overtime hours (over 40), and daily overtime hours (hours 13+ in a day) as separate line items, each with the applicable rate. The current generator applies the standard FLSA calculation; if you have Colorado daily overtime, calculate those hours separately and add them to your gross pay entry.</p>

<h3>I'm a weed dispensary manager in Denver. Will banks accept my pay stubs?</h3>
<p>It depends on the bank. Most traditional federally chartered banks remain reluctant to work with cannabis businesses due to federal banking law conflicts, even in states where cannabis is legal. However, state-chartered banks and credit unions can often serve cannabis industry employees, particularly when the employee is a W-2 wage earner rather than a business owner. If you are a salaried employee of a licensed Colorado cannabis operation, your W-2 wages are regular income, and most mortgage lenders who work with cannabis industry workers can use your pay documentation. Some national lenders decline cannabis employees; work with a Colorado-based mortgage broker who knows the local cannabis workforce landscape.</p>

<h3>Colorado's TABOR refunds mean my effective tax rate is below 4.4%. Should I adjust my stubs?</h3>
<p>TABOR refunds are an annual income tax credit on your Colorado return -- they do not affect withholding during the year. Your employer withholds at the 4.4% rate, and you receive the TABOR refund when you file your Colorado tax return. Do not adjust your generated stubs to reflect an assumed TABOR refund -- use the full 4.4% rate for withholding purposes, as that is what employers actually withhold. You will reconcile the refund at tax time.</p>

<h3>I work at a Vail ski resort and live in a ski town. Housing is extremely expensive. Any documentation tips?</h3>
<p>Mountain resort rental markets are unusual because rental costs are often extremely high relative to typical seasonal worker wages. Landlords in resort towns are accustomed to unusual housing arrangements (roommates, employee housing, etc.), but when renting independently you need solid income documentation. Generate stubs for every pay period of the season to show consistent income. If your resort provides seasonal housing and you are applying for a different rental at season-end, stubs from the just-completed season are your primary income documentation. Some resort landlords also accept employment letters confirming seasonal rehire or base wages. Our <a href="/pay-stub-for-apartment">pay stub for apartment</a> guide covers what landlords in competitive markets typically need.</p>

<h3>Does Colorado have any state disability insurance or paid family leave deductions?</h3>
<p>Colorado's Paid Family and Medical Leave Insurance (FAMLI) program launched January 1, 2023. The employee premium is 0.45% of gross wages (up to the Social Security wage base) in 2024. Both employees and employers contribute. The employee deduction appears on your pay stub as a separate "FAMLI" line, and provides up to 12 weeks (or 16 for some situations) of paid leave at 90% of wages for qualifying family and medical events. This is a relatively new addition to Colorado's payroll landscape -- workers and employers are still adapting to the new deduction. Make sure any generated stubs for 2023 dates and beyond include this Colorado FAMLI deduction if applicable.</p>

